INSERT INTO `contents` VALUES (12,'thinking_cartoon','thinking',1,'thinking',4,3),(15,'chopSticks_cartoon','chopsticks',999,'chopSticks',1,3),(17,'posting_cartoon','postin titleCartoon',1,'planning',5,3),(18,'degree_cartoon','degree',1,'degree',6,3),(22,'welcome_title','welcome',10,'<h1>Welcome!</h1>\r\n<p>Hello and welcome to the developer portfolio website for Jonny Edwards! I\'m a passionate software developer, who is always keen to learn new things and deliver great products.&nbsp; Simply put, I love what I do!&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Contents</strong></h4>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">As you\'ll see, I regularly pick up coding projects in my spare time.&nbsp; Take a look at the&nbsp;<strong><a title=\"Link to Examples Page\" href=\"../../examples\">Examples Page</a></strong> to see some of the home projects I\'ve been tinkering with recently.&nbsp; As you\'ll see, I\'m extremely experienced in <strong>C#</strong>, <strong>JS, HTML5, CSS3</strong> and <strong>PHP</strong>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Visit the&nbsp;<strong><a title=\"Link to Employment Page\" href=\"../../employment\">Employment Page</a> </strong>and you\'ll see that I\'ve been working with all aspects of <strong>Dynamic CRM 2011 </strong>and associated <strong>Enterprise Products.&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>I regularly work with <strong>C# Plugins and Workflows</strong>, middleware <strong>Windows Services</strong>, <strong>Web Forms</strong>,<strong> JavaScript</strong> and more!</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Visit the&nbsp;<strong><a title=\"Link to Education Page\" href=\"../../education\">Education Page</a></strong> for a run down of my formal and informal learning.</p>\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</h4>\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Technical Knowledge and Experience at a Glance:</strong></h4>',1,1),(23,'howdy_cartoon','howdy',1,'howdy',1,3),(24,'CNMS_solution','CNMS',30,'<h3 style=\"text-align: left;\">Details</h3>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">My solution was a composite system comprised of the following:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">A <a title=\"Link to more details about workflows.\" href=\"http://crmbook.powerobjects.com/system-administration/processes/workflows/\" target=\"_blank\">custom workflow assembly,</a> written in C#;</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">Webservices local to each of the 3 environments &ndash; Dev/Test/Live, written in C#;</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">A logging database, written in MS SQL;</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">A separately managed Windows Service, written in C#<strong>;</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3 style=\"text-align: left;\">Design Overview<img style=\"width: 100%;\" src=\"../../images/content/CNMS.svg\" alt=\"System Architecture\" /></h3>\r\n<h3>CRM Custom Workflow assembly:</h3>\r\n<p>CRM has built in workflow components for completing server-side business tasks via the GUI. Workflows, in this context, act as facades for C# classes.&nbsp; Each workflow is made of &ldquo;activities&rdquo; that essentially represent methods within these classes.&nbsp; Programmatically, custom workflow activities can be added to CRM via its SDK integration with Visual Studio. I wrote a custom activity in C# that RESTfully passes a document request from CRM to a locally hosted web service via POST. For the workflows to trigger at the correct stage within a CRM case\'s lifespan, each service that required documentation needed bespoke JavaScript and form customisation..</p>\r\n<h3>CRM Local Web Service:</h3>\r\n<p>Written in C#, the local web service receives data via POST and updates my log database accordingly.</p>\r\n<h3>Log Database:</h3>\r\n<p>A relatively simple schema consisting of a few relations centred around a log table.</p>\r\n<h3>CRM-to-Engine Web Service:</h3>\r\n<p>This is the core component of my system and is maintained on a separate server from the CRM and Sharepoint. Written in C#, it is an executable that recurrently performs a number of checks based on a timer set within its configuration parameters. The full scale of this component is beyond the scope of this document; here are the key points:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Operate between working hours stipulated within the configuration parameters (this prevents redundant exception handling during maintenance hours)</li>\r\n<li>Check for the oldest on-going workflow requests that the document engine has received but that is still marked as &ldquo;in-progress&rdquo; (if applicable).</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ul style=\"padding-left: 60px;\">\r\n<li>&nbsp;If the workflow\'s status has changed, update record.</li>\r\n<li>&nbsp;If the workflow failed, submit a new service desk call to the service desk database.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li value=\"3\">If the windows service\'s thread is available, check for any new requests (else, return). Pass the oldest of the new requests to the document engine.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ul style=\"padding-left: 60px;\">\r\n<li>Lock the thread (prevents the next service &ldquo;tick&rdquo; overwriting the current request)</li>\r\n<li>Send the request to the document engine and anticipate a GUID in response</li>\r\n<li>If a GUID is not returned or the request throws a timeout exception, submit a service desk call to the service desk database.</li>\r\n</ul>',5,2),(26,'scroll_home','HBC',10,'<h1 id=\"scroll_home\">Employment</h1>\r\n<p><strong>...More than just my bread and butter!</strong></p>',5,1),(28,'scroll_point3','pause',40,'<h4 style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>2. CRM Custom \"Pause\" Functionality</strong></h4>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Context</strong><br />A Client needed the ability for her staff to pause CRM cases mid-flow using a pause button on the CRM\'s main menu ribbon.&nbsp; This meant customer\'s could end a phone call, ring back with more details and still be marked against the same open case.&nbsp; This would prevent redundant duplicate cases against a customer record and enable a more consistent history.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Brief<br /></strong>Design a modular pause implementation that could be rolled out across different services within CRM.&nbsp; The pause button should allow staff to stop and restart cases seamlessly from almost any point within a form\'s lifespan.&nbsp; It should take consideration of existing client (JS) and server-side (Workflow/<a title=\"Description of Plugins\" href=\"http://crmbook.powerobjects.com/extending-crm/plug-in-development-and-workflow-extensions/plug-ins/\" target=\"_blank\">Plugin</a>/C#) events within the form</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong style=\"text-align: left;\">Click on the accordian below to view my solution.</strong></p>',5,1),(29,'scroll_point2','CNMS',20,'<h4 style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>1. Document Request Logging and Management System.</strong></h4>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Context:</strong><br />The CRM doesn\'t have native support for document production so the council uses a 3rd party document workflow engine in their Sharepoint environment to create letters and forms automatically.&nbsp; Systems external to Sharepoint are able to interface with this engine via SOAP request to a Web Service.&nbsp; From prior to my joining the council the CRM had been sending document production requests to the engine via AJAX to a local website (within the same server environment as the CRM), then via a POST request to the engine\'s Web Service.&nbsp; This presented several problems, most notably, that timeouts due to emergent performance issues and/or errors were not being tracked automatically.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Brief:<br /></strong>Design a robust middleware system that logged and queued document workflow requests from CRM and traced their lifecycle within the document workflow engine.<br /><br /><strong style=\"text-align: left;\">Click on the accordian below to view my solution.</strong></p>',5,1),(30,'pause_solution','pause',50,'<h3 style=\"text-align: left;\">Technical Challenges</h3>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Nearly all the services simply have an \"on create\" view and a \"read only\" view.&nbsp; re-opening a case halfway through would require the form to programmatically immitate the previous javascript events that had occurred when the user was previously engaged with the form.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>CRM does not have an out-of-the-box graphical method for adding custom buttons to its main ribbon.&nbsp; The core XML of each service requiring alteration would need editing therefore.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>The data from paused cases would need storing in the database so Users could work on other cases pending further action; the pause handler would need to perform a save event.&nbsp; However, when CRM fires a save event (programmatically or otherwise), it fires its own native save events <em>before </em>any custom save events written by the developer.&nbsp; One native line of logic prevents the form from saving if any unpopulated mandatory fields are found within the form.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>To accomodate pause functionality into some of the more complex services would require altering the bespoke C# plugins I had written for them previously.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h3 style=\"text-align: left;\">1. Reopening Cases Halfway through.</h3>\r\n<p>My team and I use an object literal pseudo-class to store each service\'s local implementation.&nbsp; Each field with an event handler on the form passes an \"execution object\" (similar to standard DOMs \"event\" object) to a single \"onChange\" method within the pseudo-class.&nbsp; Subsequently, with a minor tweak to the onChange method, I was able test whether each event-handling field had been fired or not and - if it had - passed it to the onChange method.&nbsp; This looked roughly like the below:</p>\r\n<div class=\"codeOdd\">1 // called in the Service.load method</div>\r\n<div class=\"codeEven\">2 var field, fieldEvents = [\'field1\', \'field2\', \'field3\', \'field4\'];</div>\r\n<div class=\"codeOdd\">3 for (var i in fieldEvents) {</div>\r\n<div class=\"codeEven\">4&nbsp;&nbsp; field = Xrm.Page.getAttribute(fieldEvents[i]); // similar to document.getElementById(elem)</div>\r\n<div class=\"codeOdd\">5&nbsp;&nbsp; if (field.getValue()) {</div>\r\n<div class=\"codeEven\">6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; this.onChange(field);</div>\r\n<div class=\"codeOdd\">7&nbsp;&nbsp; }</div>\r\n<div class=\"codeEven\">8 }</div>\r\n<p>The above greatly reduced the amount of refactoring required elsewhere in the form.</p>\r\n<h3>2. Altering a CRM Entity\'s Save Ribbon XML.</h3>\r\n<p>Each service in our CRM is comprised of one or more modular \"<a title=\"entities MSDN reference\" href=\"https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/gg309396%28v=crm.5%29.aspx\" target=\"_blank\">entities</a>\" containing form templates.&nbsp; I read around the subject and was able to add an icon of my own design to the form based on a Technet <a title=\"link to technet tutorial\" href=\"http://social.technet.microsoft.com/wiki/contents/articles/15439.microsoft-dynamics-crm-2011-adding-a-new-custom-ribbon-button.aspx\" target=\"_blank\">tutorial</a>.&nbsp; I assigned it to call a new \"onPause\" method within our development\'s global Javascript file (which holds tools that we use on multiple services).</p>\r\n<h3>3. Handling Save via an \"onPause\" method.</h3>\r\n<p>A mandatory field in CRM can have its requirement status altered temporarily.&nbsp; The only feasible way to handle the save therefore was to have the onPause event iterate through its hierarchy of fields removing any mandatory flags where applicable.&nbsp; Once all mandatory fields were temporarily set to not be mandatory (until next load), the pause method could call save programmatically.</p>\r\n<h3>4. Refactoring Plugin Events.</h3>\r\n<p>The most challenging part of this project was handling existing events driven by plugins (the fully programmatic C# components within CRM\'s customisation tool).&nbsp; The most complex example was a Service I had written for handling the booking of market stalls.&nbsp; The case securely passed its data on save to a WebService that updates a custom Sharepoint list for clients within our Markets team.&nbsp; By default, CRM\'s plugins rely on data from their calling context to handle data.&nbsp; Prior to implementing pause functionality, this service only tested for the creation of a case and - due to the way in which plugins behave - would not be able to capture further data from subsequent saves.&nbsp; I refactored the code to listen for and examine an SDK <a title=\"link to a synopsis of post-images\" href=\"http://msdynamics4you.blogspot.co.uk/2011/04/pre-and-post-entity-images.html\" target=\"_blank\">Post-Image</a> (effectively, data captured from the latest save trigger) and had it set to not only create new items in the Sharepoint list but to update Sharepoint lists already created from Paused requests.</p>\r\n<h3>Other Considerations.</h3>\r\n<p>It occured to me that the client had not considered what a paused case might do if the customer decided not to ring back.&nbsp; After some discussion, it was agreed that paused cases ought to cancel automatically after 2 weeks.&nbsp; This was easily solved using a CRM Workflow running a chron task; however, multiple running workflows in CRM could lead to performance issues and CRM 2011 doesn\'t have the default ability to cancel running workflows from other workflows.&nbsp; Therefore, I wrote 2 new workflow assemblies, an assembly that would store the GUID of the running workflow in a hidden field on the relevant form, and another that would retrieve the GUID from the form and use it to programmatically cancel the running workflow prematurely if the case was completed prior to the end of the fortnight.</p>',5,2),(31,'education_title','sheffield',10,'<h1>Education</h1>\r\n<p><strong>...or in my case: \"off-roading to do what you love!\"</strong></p>',6,1),(33,'education_history','education',30,'<h3>Full Education History</h3>\r\n<table width=\"100%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"4\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr valign=\"top\">\r\n<td style=\"border-top: 1px solid #000000; border-bottom: none; border-left: none; border-right: none; padding: 0.1cm 0cm 0cm 0cm;\" width=\"69%\">\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><font face=\"Arial, sans-serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 12pt;\" size=\"3\"><strong>Electronic &amp; Digital Library Management</strong></font><br /><font style=\"font-size: 10pt;\" size=\"2\">University of Sheffield</font></font></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><font face=\"Arial, sans-serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 10pt;\" size=\"2\">A CILIP accredited Librarian\'s degree with a strong computer science twist.<br /></font></font></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">My path into software development was a little unorthodox!&nbsp; I actually became interested in code while studying to become a professional academic librarian.&nbsp; I chose to do a version of the course that gave you access to Sheffields IT School.&nbsp; As it turned out, I loved IT and development so much that I more or less turned my librarial MSc into a full blown Computer Science primer!&nbsp; While at Sheffield I took pretty much every IT module I could get my hands on, including:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n<p><strong>Content Management Systems:<br /></strong>Introduced me to programming via PHP and the LAMP stack.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n<p><strong>Database Design:<br /></strong>Introduced me to all aspects of database design, allowed me to build a SQL database and write complex queries.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n<p><strong>Designing Usable Websites:<br /></strong>Introduced me to HTML5, CSS3 and principals for frontend development.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n<p><strong>Information Retrieval: Search Engines and Digital Libraries:<br /></strong>Introduced me to data parsing and allowed me to write a simple boolean search engine.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border-top: 1px solid #000000; border-bottom: none; border-left: none; border-right: none; padding: 0.1cm 0cm 0cm 0cm;\" width=\"1%\">\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border-top: 1px solid #000000; border-bottom: none; border-left: none; border-right: none; padding: 0.1cm 0cm 0cm 0cm;\" width=\"30%\">\r\n<p style=\"font-weight: normal;\" align=\"right\"><font face=\"Arial, sans-serif\"><strong><font style=\"font-size: 10pt;\" size=\"2\">(PG-Dip) Merit</font></strong><br /><font style=\"font-size: 10pt;\" size=\"2\">2012</font></font></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: none; padding: 0cm;\" colspan=\"3\" valign=\"top\" width=\"100%\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr valign=\"top\">\r\n<td style=\"border-top: 1px solid #000000; border-bottom: none; border-left: none; border-right: none; padding: 0.1cm 0cm 0cm 0cm;\" width=\"69%\">\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm; font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\"><font face=\"Arial, sans-serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 12pt;\" size=\"3\"><strong>MA Cultural Studies<br /></strong></font><font style=\"font-size: 10pt;\" size=\"2\">University of Leeds</font></font></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><font face=\"Arial, sans-serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 12pt;\" size=\"3\"><strong>BA (Hons) Cultural Studies<br /></strong></font><font style=\"font-size: 10pt;\" size=\"2\">University of Leeds</font></font></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><font face=\"Arial, sans-serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 10pt;\" size=\"2\">An interdisciplinary course examining critical, post-colonial, philosophical and literary theory. </font></font></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border-top: 1px solid #000000; border-bottom: none; border-left: none; border-right: none; padding: 0.1cm 0cm 0cm 0cm;\" width=\"1%\">\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border-top: 1px solid #000000; border-bottom: none; border-left: none; border-right: none; padding: 0.1cm 0cm 0cm 0cm;\" width=\"30%\">\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm; font-weight: normal;\" align=\"right\"><font face=\"Arial, sans-serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 10pt;\" size=\"2\"><strong>Merit</strong><br />2010</font></font></p>\r\n<p style=\"font-weight: normal;\" align=\"right\"><font face=\"Arial, sans-serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 12pt;\" size=\"3\"><strong>2:1<br /></strong></font><font style=\"font-size: 10pt;\" size=\"2\">2006</font></font></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: none; padding: 0cm;\" colspan=\"3\" valign=\"top\" width=\"100%\">&nbsp;\r\n<table width=\"100%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"4\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr valign=\"top\">\r\n<td style=\"border-top: 1px solid #000000; border-bottom: none; border-left: none; border-right: none; padding: 0.1cm 0cm 0cm 0cm;\" width=\"69%\" height=\"13\">\r\n<p style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\"><font face=\"Arial, sans-serif\"><strong><font style=\"font-size: 12pt;\" size=\"3\">3 A Levels, 1 As Level &amp; 10 GCSEs<br /></font></strong><font style=\"font-size: 10pt;\" size=\"2\">Hayes Secondary School</font></font></p>\r\n<p style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\"><font face=\"Arial, sans-serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 10pt;\" size=\"2\">Including English A Level, Maths &amp; IT GCSEs</font></font></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border-top: 1px solid #000000; border-bottom: none; border-left: none; border-right: none; padding: 0.1cm 0cm 0cm 0cm;\" width=\"1%\">\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"border-top: 1px solid #000000; border-bottom: none; border-left: none; border-right: none; padding: 0.1cm 0cm 0cm 0cm;\" width=\"30%\">\r\n<p lang=\"en-US\" style=\"widows: 2; orphans: 2;\" align=\"right\"><font face=\"Arial, sans-serif\"><font style=\"font-size: 10pt;\" size=\"2\">2001</font></font></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: none; padding: 0cm;\" colspan=\"3\" valign=\"top\" width=\"100%\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><strong>Philosophically speaking, I believe most people can learn anything if they put their mind to it.&nbsp; I don\'t think the learning has ever stopped for me; long may that be the case!</strong></p>',6,1),(34,'park','park bottomCartoon',999,'park',6,3),(35,'scroll_point4','BACAS',60,'<div id=\"pause_problem\" class=\"paragraph pause\">\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>3. Public Funeral Calendar<br /></strong></h4>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Context</strong><br />The client wanted a web-facing calendar that would enable the general public to access controlled amounts of data about publicly listed funerals.&nbsp; The diary had to be easy to use so that the less computer-literate would be able to operate it without trouble, to WAI standards and - of course - only able to see requested data.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Brief<br /></strong>Design an HTML calendar to corporate specifications that can be hosted within <a title=\"Link to HBC Main website.\" href=\"http://www.harrogate.gov.uk/Pages/default.aspx\" target=\"_blank\">Harrogate Borough Council\'s main website</a> and that accesses a proprietary system.&nbsp; The user should be able to search through a set number of weeks and to be able to search the entire result set for the surname of an individual.</p>\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: left;\">Link to <a title=\"Link to BACAS Calendar on HBC Website\" href=\"http://www1.harrogate.gov.uk/bcdiary/\" target=\"_blank\">HBC Public Funeral Calendar</a></h4>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong style=\"text-align: left;\">Click on the accordian below to view my solution.</strong></p>\r\n</div>',5,1),(36,'meta','meta bottomCartoon',999,'meta',5,3),(37,'scroll_home','examples',10,'<h1>Examples</h1>\r\n<p><strong>I\'m always keen to learn something new, here are a list of home research projects.&nbsp; Don\'t forget to check out my <a title=\"Link to my github page.\" href=\"https://github.com/Jonniosaurus\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>!</strong></p>',4,1),(38,'form_builder','FormBuilder',20,'<h3>UML Class Diagram</h3>\r\n<h3><img id=\"FormBuilderUML\" class=\"image FormBuilderUML\" src=\"../../images/content/FormBuilderUML.svg\" alt=\"FormBuilderUML\" />FormBuilder</h3>\r\n<p>The FormBuilder class expects an associative array containing a mixture of strings and FormAttributeBag instances. It iterates through the array and, if it finds a string matching an HTML form field type (e.g. \"textarea\"), attempts to build a suitable generic form component. More bespoke field arrangements are possible by passing it a list of FormAttributes.</p>\r\n<p>For example, say you want a textarea to have the wysiwyg editor <a title=\"link to TinyMCE website\" href=\"http://www.tinymce.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Tiny MCE</a> enabled on load and you have configured Tiny MCE to listen for form fields with an HTML class of \"hasMCE\",&nbsp; you could assign the field as follows:</p>\r\n<pre><code>\'content\' =&gt; new FormAttributeBag(\'textarea\', [ new FieldClass(\'hasMCE\')])</code></pre>\r\n<p>&nbsp;here is what a call would look like in its entirety</p>\r\n<div class=\"codeOdd\">1&nbsp; new FormBuilder(</div>\r\n<div class=\"codeEven\">2&nbsp; &nbsp; [</div>\r\n<div class=\"codeOdd\">3&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; \'fooGeneric\' =&gt; \'text\',</div>\r\n<div class=\"codeEven\">4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; \'fooType\' =&gt; new FormAttributeBag(</div>\r\n<div class=\"codeOdd\">5&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; \'select\', [ new FieldOptionset(</div>\r\n<div class=\"codeEven\">6&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; [\'foo\'=&gt;\'bar\', \'foo1\'=&gt;\'bar1\']),</div>\r\n<div class=\"codeOdd\">7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ]),</div>\r\n<div class=\"codeEven\">8 &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; \'fooTextArea\' =&gt; new FormAttributeBag(</div>\r\n<div class=\"codeOdd\">9&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; \'textarea\', [ new FieldClass(</div>\r\n<div class=\"codeEven\">10&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; \'mce-enabled\'),</div>\r\n<div class=\"codeOdd\">11&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \'id\' =&gt;\'hidden\'])],</div>\r\n<div class=\"codeEven\">12&nbsp;&nbsp; [\'page\', $uri], // <a title=\"Link to more details on Laravel Routing\" href=\"http://laravel.com/docs/4.2/routing\" target=\"_blank\">Laravel dynamic URL route</a></div>\r\n<div class=\"codeOdd\">13&nbsp;&nbsp; \'POST\', // Form submission type</div>\r\n<div class=\"codeEven\">14&nbsp;&nbsp; \'Submit\') // Form button label</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s assume we\'re passing the above to a View assigned to a $FooBar variable. At the View blade template end, all that needs to be called is:</p>\r\n<pre><code>{!! $FooBar-&gt;build($errors) !!}</code></pre>\r\n<p>The error variable is supplied by Laravel natively but allows the form to print tidy validation error messages to the user (the form assumes you are using bootstrap to render your pages, incidentally).</p>\r\n<h3>Data Modelling</h3>\r\n<p>Of course, sometimes a form needs to already contain data.&nbsp; Since I wanted a simple CMS to edit content on this site, I decided that the FormBuilder should be able to return a fully created page within its specified fields.&nbsp; Mercifully, Laravel\'s Form class can map its MVC Models to form fields.&nbsp; let\'s suppose we have the FormBuilder instance above and a table with matching fields called \"Test\"</p>\r\n<table cellpadding=\"10px\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr style=\"border-bottom: 2px solid #333333;\">\r\n<td><strong>Column Name <br /></strong></td>\r\n<td><strong>&nbsp;Type</strong></td>\r\n<td><strong>&nbsp;Description</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"border-bottom: 1px solid #333333;\">\r\n<td>id</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;int</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;PK</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"border-bottom: 1px solid #333333;\">\r\n<td>fooGeneric</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;varchar</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;textbox details</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"border-bottom: 1px solid #333333;\">\r\n<td>fooType</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;int</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;FK to a relation containing data types</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"border-bottom: 1px solid #333333;\">\r\n<td>fooTextArea</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;medium text</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;textarea details</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>By assigning the model\'s data to the build method, Laravel would immediately be able to map the data from the model to the fields.&nbsp; The only real customisation required would be to call a list of the types related to the Foreign Key</p>\r\n<div class=\"codeOdd\">1&nbsp; $types = DB::table(\'types\')-&gt;all()</div>\r\n<div class=\"codeEven\">2&nbsp; $typeOptions = array();</div>\r\n<div class=\"codeOdd\">3&nbsp; foreach($types as $t) { $typeOptions[$t-&gt;id] = $t-&gt;type; }</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>now the array of fields we pass to FormBuilder can contain the following</p>\r\n<pre><code>\'fooType\' =&gt; new FormAttributeBag(\'select\', [ new FieldOptionset($type) ]),\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<p>Let\'s assume that, as well as passing the $FooBar variable to the View template, we\'re going to pass a row from the Test table\'s contents via a variable called $testData. At the View blade template end, all that needs to be called is:</p>\r\n<pre><code>{!! $FooBar-&gt;build($testData, $errors) !!}</code></pre>\r\n<p>The FormBuilder class will still try and map the $testData-&gt;id to $fooType\'s select field, thus the correct optionset will be assigned.</p>',4,2),(39,'reading','reading bottomCartoon',999,'reading',4,3),(43,'scroll_point4','canvas',70,'<h4 style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Example 4: HTML5 Canvas JS Video Game Prototype</strong></h4>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">I wrote the following HTML5 video game prototype from scratch.&nbsp; It uses JavaScript class inheritance render&nbsp; \"actor\'s\" on screen with different behaviour types.&nbsp; In other words, the player and all the types of baddies inherit from type \"Actor\".&nbsp; the Actor class instantiates a number of basic movement and collision detection tasks as well as defining a bunch of useful helper functions.&nbsp; As you can see in the sample below, this means it\'s easy to support different kinds of AI on the fly for different characters.&nbsp; One baddy patrols and fire missiles, another guards a sentry point and chases after the player if they get too close and a third will pursue the player until the player can work out how to shake them.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Additionally, you\'ll note that your player will always move via the shortest route to the place you click and will never become stuck.&nbsp; This game implements&nbsp;<a title=\"Link to wiki on Dijkstra\'s Algorithm\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dijkstra\'s_algorithm\" target=\"_blank\">Dijkstra\'s Algorithm</a> for all actors.&nbsp; Both your player and the baddies that try to chase you will all attempt to get to where they want to be via the shortest possible route!</p>\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: left;\">Link to <a title=\"link to HTML5 Canvas Game\" href=\"../../resources/test-game-03/\" target=\"_blank\">Sample Canvas Game</a></h4>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Click on the accordian below to view the Actor class and its inheritors.</strong></p>',4,1),(44,'scroll_point3','nut',50,'<h4 style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Example 3: Writing a \"Sticky Notes\" program for Bash in shell<br /></strong></h4>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">I decided the best way to get my head around Bash and the basics of Linux would be to write a program in its shell.&nbsp;&nbsp; Simply put, I really really like Windows\' sticky notes program and thought it\'d be cool to write an interpretation of it for Linux terminals.&nbsp; Sometimes I like to write up a little tit-bit of information without having a piece of paper to hand.&nbsp; I was looking for something that would be super easy to operate and revise. The result was a discrete program called \"Nut\" which I still use to this day!&nbsp; The source is available on my page at&nbsp;<a title=\"Link to nut project on Github\" href=\"https://github.com/Jonniosaurus/nut\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Click on the accordian below to view a screenshot in which I perform a few simple Nut Tasks.</strong></p>',4,1),(45,'nut_screenshot','nut',60,'<img style=\"position: relative; width: 100%;\" src=\"../../images/content/nutScreenshot.png\" alt=\"Screenshot of my using my shell program \" />',4,2),(46,'scroll_point2','angular',30,'<h4 style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Example 2: Angular CV Sample with JSON backend<br /></strong></h4>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">I wanted to learn Bootstrap and Angular so I set myself a project to write a little sample CV that would record data in a JSON file.</p>\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: left;\">Link to <a title=\"Link to Dynamic Form Sample\" href=\"../../resources/jonathan-edwards-cv\" target=\"_blank\">Test CV Sample</a></h4>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Click on the accordian below to view the corresponding JSON data:</strong></p>',4,1),(47,'angular_json','angular',40,'<p><iframe style=\"position: relative; width: 3000px; height: 1000px; border: none;\" src=\"/resources/index.txt\"></iframe></p>',4,8),(48,'canvas_actor','actor',80,'<p><iframe style=\"width: 1500px; height: 6200px; border: none;\" src=\"/resources/Actor.txt\"></iframe></p>',4,8),(49,'bereavement_solution','BACAS',70,'<p><font size=\"2\"><font face=\"Arial, sans-serif\">The client and I liaised on several occasions to work out precise specifications.&nbsp; The data that I would need to access was hosted on an older system with little documentation.&nbsp; Subsequently, the data required careful investigation to ascertain the best approach to querying it.&nbsp; I coded a view into the database that would allow me to make precise, simple and secure queries at the code end.<br /></font></font></p>\r\n<p><font size=\"2\"><font face=\"Arial, sans-serif\">The UI was written in 2 parts with C# using MS Web Forms.&nbsp; One component focuses on building a calendar that is visible to the public and the other is accessible as an AJAX request via the search functionality at the top of the calendar.&nbsp; The latter is returned to the user via a modal window I coded myself.</font></font></p>\r\n<p><font size=\"2\"><font face=\"Arial, sans-serif\">I added a number of JavaScript components to make the search functionality as smooth and user friendly as possible. For example, the modal window can be shut using either the close button, clicking outside of the modal box or by hitting Escape.</font></font></p>',5,2),(50,'scroll_point5','housing',80,'<h4 style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>4. Designing a \"Shopping Cart\" for a Waste Container Service<br /></strong></h4>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Context</strong> <br />A client required that a CRM service be able to record and take payments for requests from the public for waste container services.&nbsp; The CRM would need to make provisions for handling complex queries with numerous permutations that could be altered at a later date (if for example issuing policies changed).</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Brief<br /></strong>Design a service that could handle multiple requests for multiple different items, keep track of the amount of money due (where applicable) and pass on requests to the various parties responsible for actioning.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong style=\"text-align: left;\">Click on the accordian below to view my solution.</strong></p>',5,1),(52,'scroll_point1','website',15,'<h4 style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Example 1: This Web Site\'s Form Builder component</strong></h4>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Backend: <strong>PHP</strong> using Laravel <strong>5.1 MVC</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Frontend: <strong>JS, HTML5</strong> & <strong>CSS</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Biggest Achievement: writing my own custom form builder for handling HTML forms on the underlying CMS.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Laravel supports a simple HTML <a title=\"Link to Laravel documentation on Form & HTML classes\" href=\"http://laravel.com/docs/4.2/html\" target=\"_blank\">tag builder</a> for generating form elements text areas and so forth using its blade templating (which is similar to ASP\'s Razor technology).   However, by default, it doesn\'t support any kind of automated form building.  By default therefore - if I want to generate a bunch of different forms for managing data on this site - I have to manually code out the layout for each page.  I decided that it\'d be less repetitive to code some helper classes that would generate forms for me.</p>\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: left;\">Link to <a title=\"Link to Dynamic Form Sample\" href=\"examples/samples/form-sample\" target=\"_blank\">Dynamic Form Sample</a></h4>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong style=\"text-align: left;\">Click on the accordian below for more detail about my Form Building Classes in Laravel.</strong></p>',4,7),(53,'scroll_menu','local',13,'<h4 id=\"scroll_call1\" class=\"scroll_menu\"><strong>Example 1: This Web Site\'s Form Builder Component</strong></h4>\r\n<h4 id=\"scroll_call2\" class=\"scroll_menu\"><strong>Example 2: Angular CV Sample with JSON Backend<br /></strong></h4>\r\n<h4 id=\"scroll_call3\" class=\"scroll_menu\"><strong>Example 3: Writing a \"Sticky Notes\" Program for Bash in Shell</strong></h4>\r\n<h4 id=\"scroll_call4\" class=\"scroll_menu\"><strong>Example 4: HTML5 Canvas JS Videogame Prototype</strong></h4>\r\n<h4 id=\"scroll_call5\" class=\"scroll_menu\"><strong>Example 5: A helper class for Dynamic CRM</strong></h4>\r\n<h4 id=\"scroll_call6\" class=\"scroll_menu\"><strong>Example 6: This Web Site\'s JavaScript Components</strong></h4>',4,1),(54,'scroll_point5','CRM',100,'<h4 style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Example 5: writing a helper class for Dynamic CRM:<br /></strong></h4>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">I had an idea for the CRM we use at work that, sadly, was just too late in the day to be implemented.&nbsp; It\'s a shame to have a nice piece of code put to waste however so I wanted to add it here.&nbsp; The premise was - in a similar fashion to the JS model I have designed for this site - was to host a static \"Global\" class that would host generic helper functions in one location and have each local implementation inherit from it.&nbsp; Below is the boiler plate.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Click on the accordian below to view the JS boiler plate.</strong></p>',4,1),(55,'Dynamic_CRM','CRM',110,'<p><iframe style=\"position: relative; border: none; width: 1500px; height: 2600px;\" src=\"/resources/CRMSampleLibrary.txt\"></iframe></p>',4,8),(56,'scroll_return1','scroll_return',23,'back to top',4,6),(57,'scroll_return2','',45,'back to top',4,6),(58,'scroll_return3','',65,'back to top',4,6),(59,'scroll_return4','',85,'back to top',4,6),(60,'scroll_return5','',115,'back to top',4,6),(61,'scroll_point6','website_js',120,'<h4 style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Example 6: This Web Site\'s JavaScript Components<br /></strong></h4>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">This website uses a Javascript library that I designed from scratch.&nbsp; All animation events are handled using my implementation of the method illustrated in the <a title=\"link to javascript.info animation tutorial\" href=\"http://javascript.info/tutorial/animation\" target=\"_blank\">javascript.info animation tutorial</a>, no JQuery is required and all components are compatible with all modern mainstream browsers.&nbsp; While I have no qualm with working with JQuery, I do maintain that less is more and it isn\'t really necessary on most small developments.&nbsp; JQuery, even in it\'s most stripped-down form is a large library to lug on to slower computers.&nbsp; With a little know-how and a <a title=\"link to wiki: Keep It Simple Stupid!\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KISS_principle\" target=\"_blank\">KISS-pincipled</a> mentality, you can do an awful lot with JS-DOM.&nbsp; (<strong>NB</strong>&nbsp; To demonstrate that I am able to use JQuery, you can see it\'s presence on the <a title=\"link to CV Sample\" href=\"../../resources/jonathan-edwards-cv\" target=\"_blank\">CV sample</a> above).</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Click the accordian below to see a walk-through of an animation on this website.</strong></p>',4,1),(62,'website_js','website_js',130,'<p>Let\'s talk about the accordian you just clicked in order to view this content!</p>\r\n<p><strong>Pre-Render:</strong></p>\r\n<p>All accordian components are flagged on the database with a \"collapsible\" flag.&nbsp; This tells the main view renderer to present the contents of the accordian in a certain way:</p>\r\n<pre>&lt;div class=\"collapsible\"&gt;<br />&nbsp; &lt;div class=\"collapser\"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Click to Expand&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;<br />&nbsp; &lt;div class=\"collapsee\"&gt;Content goes in here&lt;/div&gt;<br />&lt;/div&gt;</pre>\r\n<p>As you\'ve probably guessed, the \"collapser\" component is the part you click that passes a callback to the event handler on the form while the \"collapsee\" is the component on which the event will have agency.</p>\r\n<p><strong>On Load:</strong></p>\r\n<p>On page load, an event is assigned to each component belonging to the \"collapser\" class; additionally, a JSON object is recorded registering the default height of each collapsee on the page (to a max height of 500px).</p>\r\n<pre><code>{<br />  \"example1_collapsee\":\"235\",<br />  \"example2_collapsee\":\"500\",<br />  \"exampleEtc_collapsee\":\"456\",<br />}</code></pre>\r\n<p><strong>On Click:</strong></p>\r\n<p>When the collapser component is clicked, it triggers Action.collapsibleEvent(); however, because it was assigned to the element in question on load, the method is now assigned to the caller object (the \"collapser\"), rather than the original Action object.&nbsp; This means we can grab the collapsee component by calling the helper function Core.get.id (a shorthand for document.getElementById) and passing it <em>this</em>.id.replace(\'_collapser\', \'_collapsee\') as below:</p>\r\n<pre><code>var collapsee = Core.get.id(this.id.replace(\'_collapser\', \'_collapsee\'));</code></pre>\r\n<p>Now we can glean the height of the collapsee and work out whether we want to expand it or collapse it accordingly.&nbsp; If the height is 0px we expand, otherwise we collapse.&nbsp; However, if we\'re collapsing the component the browser has no idea whether a previous expand event is still in process.&nbsp; Likewise, the browser has no idea how much we want to expand the collapsee component if it is fully collapsed.&nbsp; The JSON recorded on load comes in to play.</p>\r\n<p><strong>JSON register:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The JSON height register resolves effectively tells the event handler \"if your height is currently 0px, expand the menu until it reaches the recorded height in my record.&nbsp; Else, if your current height is equal to the height on my record, start a collapse.&nbsp; In <em>all </em>other circumstances do nothing.\"</p>',4,2),(63,'scroll_return6','scroll_return',135,'back to top',4,6),(64,'git_link','git',140,'<h4><strong>Link to <a title=\"Link to my github page.\" href=\"https://github.com/Jonniosaurus\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a></strong></h4>',4,1),(65,'scroll_point1','Harrogate_job borderedBottom',15,'<h3 style=\"text-align: left;\">Software Developer - Harrogate Borough Council. 05/13 - Present</h3>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">My work at Harrogate Borough council revolves around the development and maintenance of <strong>C#</strong> and <strong>JavaScript</strong> solutions. It requires me to work with all aspects of the MS Web stack.&nbsp; I have engaged with numerous technologies including <strong>HTML5</strong>, <strong>CSS3</strong>, <strong>SOAP</strong>/<strong>WSDL</strong>/<strong>XML</strong>,&nbsp;<strong>LADP</strong>, <strong>JSON</strong>, <strong>REST</strong>,&nbsp;<strong>SQL</strong>/<strong>TSQL</strong>, <strong>ASP</strong> <strong>Web Forms</strong> and to engage with <strong>MVC</strong> design principals My core responsibilites are:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">Leading the development of the Council\'s Content Relationship Manager (<a title=\"Link to Dynamic CRM Wiki article\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microsoft_Dynamics_CRM\" target=\"_blank\">Dynamic CRM 2011</a>) which sees me regularly working with a number of <strong>.NET</strong> technologies (for example, the <strong>CRM SDK</strong> and <strong>WCF</strong>).<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">Liaising with clients and attempting to analyse and deliver relevant solutions to their needs.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">Developing middleware solutions (see example 1 below) for interfacing between <strong>CRM </strong>and proprietary systems.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">Developing customer-facing software such as the <a title=\"BACAS Funeral Calendar\" href=\"http://www1.harrogate.gov.uk/bcdiary/\" target=\"_blank\">BACAS Funeral Calendar</a> to both client and corporate specifications.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">Interacting with a number of database environments and proprietary database schemas in <strong>Oracle </strong>and <strong>MS SQL</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Below are a series of project examples demonstrating the work I was tasked with and my actions.&nbsp; click on the collapsible components to view detailed information.</p>',5,1),(66,'scroll_return1','',16,'back to top',5,6),(67,'scroll_return2','',35,'back to top',5,6),(68,'scroll_return3','',55,'back to top',5,6),(69,'scroll_return4','',75,'back to top',5,6),(70,'waste_container_solution','housing',90,'<h3 style=\"text-align: left;\">Technical Challenges</h3>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The linearity of CRM\'s native form controls would make it difficult to take multiple transactions in one form.  Furthermore, the schema behind Dynamic CRM 2011 is fairly rigid.  changing field types and field order, and changing the JavaScript involved therein would be fairly difficult.  I needed a generic solution that could take multiple queries and that would be quick and relatively painless to modify.</p>\r\n<h3 style=\"text-align: left;\">Writing a Shopping Cart</h3>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">I decided to build an IFrame web resource for CRM, that mimicked the UI, but would take multiple requests and generate query forms on the fly.  Suppose a customer needed an additional container of some description, the user would select the option from the shopping cart and then a form would render beneath the cart for the user to fill out.  Once the form was complete, the request was added to the cart and the total cost re-evaluated. </p>\r\n<img style=\"position: relative; width: 100%;\" src=\"../../images/content/ShoppingCartModel.svg\" alt=\"Model of Shopping Cart IFrame\" />\r\n<h3 style=\"text-align: left;\">Details</h3>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">I wrote the IFrame component in C# using web forms.  The front end was managed with JavaScript.  I used a hidden JSON field in CRM to maintain communications between the IFrame and CRM; this meant no additional back end or cookies were required to store data, it was all managed discretely within a case.  Finally, I also had to write a custom method for interfacing with our existing payment plugin.</p>',5,8),(71,'scroll_return5','',95,'back to top',5,6),(72,'scroll_menu_employment','',12,'<div id=\"scroll_menu\" class=\"paragraph local\">\r\n<h4 id=\"scroll_call1\" class=\"scroll_menu\"><str